#Calculate the Interquartile Range (IQR) and Identify Outliers
# Calculate Q1, Q3, and IQR
Q1 = df['TotalCharges'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df['TotalCharges'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

# Determine outliers using IQR
lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

print(f"The 25th percentile (Q1) of Total Charges is: {Q1}")
print(f"The 75th percentile (Q3) of Total Charges is: {Q3}")
print(f"The Interquartile Range (IQR) of Total Charges is: {IQR}")
print(f"Values below {lower_bound} and above {upper_bound} could be considered outliers.")

The 75th percentile (Q3) of Total Charges is: 3794.7375

#Calculate the IQR for Both Variables and Identify Outliers
# Calculate IQR for MonthlyCharges
Q1_MC = df['MonthlyCharges'].quantile(0.25)
Q3_MC = df['MonthlyCharges'].quantile(0.75)
IQR_MC = Q3_MC - Q1_MC

# Calculate IQR for tenure
Q1_tenure = df['tenure'].quantile(0.25)
Q3_tenure = df['tenure'].quantile(0.75)
IQR_tenure = Q3_tenure - Q1_tenure

# Determine outliers using IQR for both fields
lower_bound_MC = Q1_MC - 1.5 * IQR_MC
upper_bound_MC = Q3_MC + 1.5 * IQR_MC
lower_bound_tenure = Q1_tenure - 1.5 * IQR_tenure
upper_bound_tenure = Q3_tenure + 1.5 * IQR_tenure

print(f"Monthly Charges - 25th percentile (Q1): {Q1_MC}, 75th percentile (Q3): {Q3_MC}, IQR: {IQR_MC}")
print(f"Monthly Charges outliers are values below {lower_bound_MC} and above {upper_bound_MC}.")
print(f"Tenure - 25th percentile (Q1): {Q1_tenure}, 75th percentile (Q3): {Q3_tenure}, IQR: {IQR_tenure}")
print(f"Tenure outliers are values below {lower_bound_tenure} and above {upper_bound_tenure}.")

Monthly Charges - 25th percentile (Q1): 35.5, 75th percentile (Q3): 89.85, IQR: 54.349999999999994
Monthly Charges outliers are values below -46.02499999999999 and above 171.375.
Tenure - 25th percentile (Q1): 9.0, 75th percentile (Q3): 55.0, IQR: 46.0
Tenure outliers are values below -60.0 and above 124.0.

Monthly Charges outliers are values below -46.02499999999999 and above 171.375.¶

Tenure outliers are values below -60.0 and above 124.0.¶

Conclusion , for our nominal values , outliers , not present , so our ML models will not disrupt too much or give more errors¶

# detailed vaules of categorical columns 

# Identify categorical columns excluding 'customerID'
categorical_columns = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
categorical_columns = [col for col in categorical_columns if col != 'customerID']

# Create figure with appropriate size based on the number of categorical columns
fig, ax = plt.subplots(len(categorical_columns), 1, figsize=(10, 5 * len(categorical_columns)))

# Iterate through the list of categorical columns to create count plots
for i, column in enumerate(categorical_columns):
    # Create countplot
    sns.countplot(y=column, data=df, ax=ax[i] if len(categorical_columns) > 1 else ax)
    ax_temp = ax[i] if len(categorical_columns) > 1 else ax
    
    # Set title and labels
    ax_temp.set_title(f'{column} Distribution')
    ax_temp.set_xlabel('')
    ax_temp.set_ylabel('')
    
    # Add value labels next to each bar
    for p in ax_temp.patches:
        ax_temp.annotate(f"{int(p.get_width())}",  # Extract count
                   (p.get_x() + p.get_width(), p.get_y() + p.get_height()/2),  # Position for label
                   xytext=(5, 0),  # Distance from bar
                   textcoords='offset points',
                   va='center',  # Center vertically in bar
                   ha='left')  # Align text left

# Adjust layout to not overlap graphs
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

14 -¶

Dummy Variables:¶

Converts all categorical variables into dummy/indicator variables using pd.get_dummies. It automatically handles all categorical columns except the 'customerID' to avoid unnecessary expansion. drop_first=True is used to avoid multicollinearity by dropping the first category in each feature. Scaling:

Uses StandardScaler from sklearn.preprocessing to standardize the numerical columns ('tenure', 'MonthlyCharges', 'TotalCharges') by removing the mean and scaling to unit variance. Check Processed Data:

Displays the first few rows of the processed dataset. Prints detailed information about the new DataFrame, including data types and the presence of any null values. Save Processed Data:

Saves the fully processed data to a CSV file, ensuring that all transformations are preserved for future analysis or model training.

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Convert categorical variables to dummy/indicator variables
categorical_columns = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns.drop('customerID')  # Exclude 'customerID'
df_encoded = pd.get_dummies(df, columns=categorical_columns, drop_first=True)  # Create dummies and drop the first to avoid dummy trap

# Scaling numerical features
scaler = StandardScaler()
numerical_columns = ['tenure', 'MonthlyCharges', 'TotalCharges']
df_encoded[numerical_columns] = scaler.fit_transform(df_encoded[numerical_columns])

# Check the processed data
print("Processed Data:")
print(df_encoded.head())
print("\n")

# Summary of the new dataframe
print("New DataFrame Information:")
print(df_encoded.info())
print("\n")

# Save the fully processed DataFrame for further analysis
df_encoded.to_csv('D02fully_processed_telco_data.csv', index=False)

import pandas as pd
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler, OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.impute import SimpleImputer
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline

# Create a ColumnTransformer to apply transformations to the respective column types
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[
        ('num', MinMaxScaler(), numerical_columns),
        ('cat', OneHotEncoder(drop='first'), categorical_columns)
    ])

# Apply transformations
df_processed = preprocessor.fit_transform(df)

# Generate new column names for the transformed features
new_categorical_features = preprocessor.named_transformers_['cat'].get_feature_names_out(categorical_columns)
new_column_names = numerical_columns + list(new_categorical_features)

# Convert the processed numpy array back to a DataFrame
df_processed = pd.DataFrame(df_processed, columns=new_column_names)

# Check the processed data
print("Processed Data:")
print(df_processed.head())
print("\n")

# Summary of the new dataframe
print("New DataFrame Information:")
print(df_processed.info())
print("\n")

# Save the fully processed DataFrame for further analysis
df_processed.to_csv('D03Mainfully_processed_telco_data.csv', index=False)

print("Data preprocessing complete and saved to 'D03Mainfully_processed_telco_data.csv'.")
